# ============================================================
# BLOCK 3 — JOB ARGUMENTS
# ============================================================
# When AWS runs the Glue job it passes information through arguments —
# like telling the job which file to process. Think of it like calling
# a function with parameters.
#
# getResolvedOptions reads two REQUIRED arguments:
#   JOB_NAME  : Glue injects this automatically — the name of the job
#   input_key : the S3 path of the file to process e.g. raw/2026/03/17/data.tab
#
# WHY NOT HARDCODE THE FILE PATH?
#   The same job should work for any file on any date. Today it processes
#   March 17's file. Tomorrow March 18's. Only the argument changes.
#
# --force is handled separately because getResolvedOptions raises an
# exception if you ask for an argument that was not passed. Since --force
# is optional we inspect sys.argv (the raw argument list) directly.
#
# _flag() accepts three valid forms:
#   --force          (bare flag — presence alone means true)
#   --force true     (explicit true)
#   --force True     (capital T also accepted)
#
# ⚠ LIMITATION:
#   argv.index(name) finds only the FIRST occurrence of --force.
#   If someone accidentally passes it twice, the second is ignored.
#   Fine for now but worth knowing.
#
# ⚠ IMPROVEMENT (from code review):
#   --input_key should have NO default value in the Glue job config.
#   Forcing the caller to always provide it makes the pipeline explicit
#   and prevents accidentally reprocessing a stale hardcoded file.
# ============================================================
